{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649026"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18343"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18343"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.03,0,0.03,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79329"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64651"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79329"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents with pain in the outer aspect of his right leg, just above his ankle. The pain started after he stumbled on some loose rocks whilst walking and twisted his ankle. On examination there is tenderness on the lateral aspect of his leg, immediately above his ankle. He has difficulty turning his ankle outwards.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely to be involved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibularis brevis","Flexor hallucis longus","Gastrocnemius","Soleus","Tibialis anterior"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibularis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is located in the lateral compartment of the leg. It is responsible for eversion of the foot and assists in stabilising the ankle joint. In this scenario, the patient\u0027s lateral ankle pain and difficulty with eversion suggest involvement of the fibularis brevis muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis anterior\u003C/strong\u003E is located in the anterior compartment of the leg and is primarily responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrocnemius\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esoleus\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are located in the posterior compartment of the leg and are involved in plantarflexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor hallucis longus\u003C/strong\u003E is also located in the posterior compartment and is responsible for flexing the big toe.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The lateral compartment of the leg contains the fibularis longus and fibularis brevis muscles.","The fibularis brevis muscle is responsible for eversion of the foot and plays a role in stabilising the ankle."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64651"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64651"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:40:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T09:41:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79329"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23: